<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">January 31, 2024</h2>
<a href="/lit-hub-daily-january-31-2024/"><img class="wp-image-232655 size-thumbnail aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Screenshot-2024-01-30-at-8.57.03-PM-150x150.png" alt="" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li>Russia has placed London-based, <a href="https://pen.org/press-release/russia-places-best-selling-detective-novelist-boris-akunin-on-its-wanted-list/" class="external" target="_blank">best-selling novelist Boris Akunin on its Most Wanted List</a>.</li>
 	<li>Good to know! <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/01/30/books/penguin-random-house-nihar-malaviya.html" class="external" target="_blank">Penguin Random House’s CEO “doesn’t like to talk about himself.”</a></li>
 	<li>Kathryn VanArendonk <a href="https://www.vulture.com/article/sarah-j-maas-acotar-crescent-city-new-book.html?origSession=D230829YotSGk6X4iBHhUfbKyHZmJmIlqCPJxNyUGAU2l3HUb8%3D&amp;_gl=1*1cwb0zw*_ga*MTMzNzc5ODgxMy4xNjkxMzY4MDE1*_ga_DNE38RK1HX*MTcwNjY0MzQyOC4xNTAuMC4xNzA2NjQzNDMwLjU4LjAuMA..#_ga=2.223029467.1943140972.1706475906-1337798813.1691368015" class="external" target="_blank">profiles “the mortal queen of faerie smut” Sarah J. Maas</a>.</li>
</ul>
<a title="LitHub Daily: May 1, 2015" href="/lit-hub-daily-january-31-2024/"><button>More News</button></a></li>
	    			</ul>
	    		</div>
	    	</div>
	    </div>
    </div>
